snippet.textDisplay: I'd just like to say that this song is not bad at all, the instruments were so awesome- it's meant to be a rock song- obviously it'll be loud. I don't like rock music but this song is awesome because the ethnic instruments retain the Pakistani essence well, while successfully amalgamating the western side to this song with it. She's a powerful singer. You can't just expect coke studio to give you the same type of songs?? They're experimenting, which is really good for the industry.

snippet.textDisplay:
The tune does have merit but Meesha is unnecessarily nasal. I don't know why Pakistani singers (Atif, even Rahat, and now Meesha) are inspired somehow by Himesh Reshammiya style of singing.
Also, the Sitar is completely out of place with the mood of the song. It is clearly forcibly inserted, just to give it a feel of thrusting heritage with contemporary stuff to achieve some kind of fusion (read: khichrhi).
snippet.textOriginal:
The tune does have merit but Meesha is unnecessarily nasal. I don't know why Pakistani singers (Atif, even Rahat, and now Meesha) are inspired somehow by Himesh Reshammiya style of singing.
Also, the Sitar is completely out of place with the mood of the song. It is clearly forcibly inserted, just to give it a feel of thrusting heritage with contemporary stuff to achieve some kind of fusion (read: khichrhi).
